[[File:30 Gresham Street, January 2018 01.jpg|thumb|30 Gresham Street, January 2018]]
'''30 Gresham Street''' is an office building in [[Gresham Street]] in the [[City of London]] of 386,000 sq ft<ref>"Buildings going up despite City glut", Jenny Davey, ''The Times'', 20 October 2003, p. 25.</ref> developed by [[Land Securities]] in 2002-03 and occupied by [[Commerzbank]] and [[Investec]].<ref>[http://openoffices.com/office/30-gresham-street-city-of-london-ec2-london-1749 30 Gresham Street, City of London, EC2, London.] Open Offices. Retrieved 7 January 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.costar.co.uk/en/assets/news/2016/March/Investec-agrees-100000-sq-ft-off-market-deal/ Investec agrees 100,000 sq ft off-market move.] James Buckley, CoStar, 16 March 2016. Retrieved 7 January 2017.</ref> When built, it was described as "the biggest speculative office development in the capital".<ref>"Gamble on Gresham St." ''The Times'', 22 May 2003, p. 35.</ref> The building is bounded in the south by [[Russia Row]] and [[Trump Street]], in the east by [[Lawrence Lane, London|Lawrence Lane]], and in the west by [[Milk Street, London|Milk Street]]. It is on the site of the former [[Blossom's Inn]] as well as a number of other small alleys and courts such as Robin Hood Court, Russia Court, Mumford Court and Castle Court.

It replaced an earlier building of the same name which became known as the "Night Club in the City".<ref name="Kyna">{{cite book|author=Kynaston, David.|title=The City Of London Vol. IV A Club No More 1945-2000.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NW9zBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334|year=2002|publisher=Pimlico|location=London|isbn=978-1-4481-1232-6|page=334}}</ref>

