'''Jacques Weulersse''' (born February 11, 1905 in [[Paris]]) was a [[French people|French]] geographer of [[Africa]] and the [[Arab world]].<ref name="article">{{cite journal |last=Colin |first=Élicio |date=1947 |title=Jacques Weulersse (1905-1946) |url=http://www.persee.fr/doc/geo_0003-4010_1947_num_56_301_12439 |journal=[[Annales de Géographie]] |publisher=|volume=56 |issue=301 |pages= 53–54 |issn=}}</ref>
==Biography== He received his bachelor's degree in history and geography in 1928. He became a professor at [[Chartres]], and subsequently the [[Lycée Condorcet]]. He obtained his Doctorate of Letters in 1941, becoming master of colonial geography at [[Aix-Marseille University]] in 1943.<ref name="article"/> He died in 1946.
== Works == * ''Le pays des Alaouites'', Thèse, Tours, Arrault, 1940, 2 volumes, 422 p. * ''Noirs et Blancs. A travers l'Afrique nouvelle de Dakar au Cap'', Paris, Armand Colin, 1931, 242 p. (Re-printed 1993, Paris)
